  "prompt": "Why India's performance is still poor in olympics?",
  "response": "India's performance in the Olympics has historically been less impressive compared to some other nations, and there are several factors that contribute to this situation:\n\n1. **Funding and Infrastructure**:\n   - Sports infrastructure in India is often inadequate. Many athletes do not have access to world-class facilities for training and competition.\n   - Investment in sports is relatively low compared to countries that consistently perform well in the Olympics. This includes funding for equipment, coaches, and support staff.\n\n2. **Talent Identification and Development**:\n   - There is a lack of systematic talent identification and development programs. Many potential athletes are not discovered or nurtured at a young age.\n   - Grassroots-level sports programs are not as widespread or effective, leading to a smaller pool of high-performance athletes.\n\n3. **Coaching and Support**:\n   - The quality and availability of coaching can be inconsistent. There is often a shortage of experienced and qualified coaches.\n   - Support systems, including sports science, nutrition, and psychological support, are not as developed as they are in leading sports nations.\n\n4. **Cultural Factors**:\n   - There is often more emphasis on academic success rather than sports. Many talented athletes abandon their sporting ambitions due to societal pressures to focus on education and secure stable careers.\n   - Popularity and media coverage of sports other than cricket (which is the dominant sport in India) are relatively low, affecting motivation and support for athletes in other disciplines.\n\n5. **Government Policies and Management**:\n   - Sports administration and governance can be inefficient and sometimes plagued by corruption, affecting the distribution of resources and support to the athletes.\n   - Policies and initiatives to promote sports at the national level may not be effectively implemented or sustained.\n\n6. **Socioeconomic Factors**:\n   - Many athletes come from economically disadvantaged backgrounds and face financial struggles that hinder their ability to train and compete at the highest level.\n   - Lack of sponsorship and financial support can limit opportunities for athletes to participate in international competitions and gain exposure.\n\nAddressing these issues requires a concerted effort from the government, sports organizations, corporate sponsors, and society at large to create an environment where athletes can thrive and compete on the global stage.",
